    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  
  <p>A man sits alone in a train switching station. He's been told he's here for a focus group about California's high-speed rail project. A worker showed him the lever, explained how it diverts trains between tracks, then stepped out. On the monitor, a train appears. Five workers on the main line. One on the side track. The train is not stopping.</p>
  <p>He does not pull the lever.</p>
  <p>Neither does the next person. Or the next. In Michael Stevens' 2017 experiment, the first to put real-seeming stakes behind philosophy's favorite hypothetical, five of seven participants watched what they believed was a runaway train bearing down on five human beings and chose to do nothing. One who <em>did</em> pull it said the decision had to be immediate, that five families' lives were in his hands. He pulled it and sat with what he'd done. The majority just sat.</p>
  <p>A clinical psychologist had screened every participant. They weren't confused. They were afraid. Afraid of the lever, not the math. When the debrief came, each of the five had a story: the workers would hear the train, safety systems would engage, <em>somebody</em> would handle it. Five different alibis for the same crime of hesitation.</p>
  <p>On surveys, 90% of people say they'd pull it. In rooms with real levers, 71% don't. When researchers in Belgium ran a version with actual mice and actual electric shocks (one mouse or five), 84% pressed the button. Rodent stakes sharpened the math. Human stakes blurred it. There's a dissertation in that gap, and it has nothing to do with ethics.</p>
</section>

<section id="one-death-or-five" class="reveal">
  <h2>One Death or Five</h2>
  <p>Every semester, in every intro ethics course on earth, the trolley problem gets presented as a genuine stalemate. Utilitarians pull the lever. Deontologists don't. Nobody wins. The professor shrugs. The students leave thinking moral philosophy is a coin flip dressed in Latin.</p>
  <p>This framing is a lie of omission. Sixty-eight percent of professional philosophers say pull the lever. That's a supermajority <em>within the profession whose entire job is to find complications</em>. Imagine 68% of economists agreeing on a policy. You'd call it a consensus and move on. Philosophy gives itself permission to treat the same margin as an open question.</p>
  <p>The math, stripped bare: five strangers, one stranger, no other information. The person who does not pull the lever has chosen, through inaction, to let four additional people die. Not choosing is a choice. It's just a choice with a better alibi.</p>
  <p>The philosophical cover for this inaction has a name: the acts/omissions distinction. Killing someone, the argument goes, is categorically different from letting someone die. Stated cleanly, it almost sounds reasonable. Applied to any real scenario, it collapses. A lifeguard who watches a swimmer drown because "I didn't push him in" has not achieved innocence. She has found a technicality. An ER team that won't perform a risky surgery, guaranteeing the patient dies in the waiting room instead of on the table, hasn't avoided a death. They've moved it to a room with less paperwork.</p>
  <p>When toddlers are given a version of the trolley problem, they pick up the single person and place them on the track with the other five. Then they let the train hit everyone. This contributes nothing to the philosophical debate. It is, by a wide margin, the funniest finding in the entire ethics literature.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-lever-isn-t-cold-your-flinch-isn-t-wisdom" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Lever Isn't Cold. Your Flinch Isn't Wisdom.</h2>
  <p>Here is what the psychology actually shows. Cognitive overload pushes people toward inaction. Death reminders push people toward inaction. Emotional priming pushes people toward inaction. The ventromedial prefrontal cortex, the brain region that processes emotional responses, is the thing standing between you and the lever. People with damage to that region are <em>more</em> likely to pull it. The moral feeling people trust most in this scenario is, measurably, a neurological flinch.</p>
  <p>One study found that people who chose the utilitarian option scored higher on psychopathy scales. This finding has been gleefully misread by approximately everyone who has ever cited it. The actual result: people who override emotional discomfort to reach a better outcome share one trait with people who lack empathy. Reduced empathic distress. A trait also shared by surgeons, paramedics, combat medics, and triage nurses. The entire architecture of emergency medicine depends on people who can feel terrible and act anyway. We don't diagnose them. We give them the hardest jobs and thank them afterward.</p>
  <p>The five people in Stevens' switching station weren't engaged in moral reasoning. They were writing alibis in real time. "The workers will see it coming." "There must be a backup system." Each excuse had the same function: to make paralysis feel principled. This is not philosophy. It is the structure of every bystander failure ever studied, from Kitty Genovese to the present.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-fat-man-is-a-different-case" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Fat Man Is a Different Case</h2>
  <p>Opponents of the utilitarian answer always reach for the same escalation. Same trolley, but now instead of a lever, you push a large man off a bridge to stop it with his body. Most people refuse. Philosophers call this proof that raw consequentialism breaks down.</p>
  <p>On this narrow point, they're right. The lever redirects a threat already in motion. Pushing a man off a bridge turns a bystander into a barricade. One is deflection. The other is conscription. Kant's prohibition on using people as mere means applies to the second case with full force. The organ-harvesting version (kill one healthy patient, distribute his organs to five dying ones) makes the same point so sharply that it needs no commentary.</p>
  <p>But here's what the fat man does <em>not</em> prove: that the lever case is also ambiguous. In the standard scenario, you are redirecting a preexisting threat. The one person's death is a foreseeable consequence, not the mechanism of rescue. Even Catholic moral theology, via the doctrine of double effect, endorses this distinction. When both the Vatican and the utilitarian tradition land on the same side of a question, the question is probably settled.</p>
  <p>Sixty years of philosophy papers have treated the lever and the fat man as a single problem. They are not. One asks whether you can redirect harm. The other asks whether you can manufacture a human shield. Conflating them is how a solved problem stays "open" across six decades of tenure files.</p>
</section>

<section id="nobody-memes-a-hard-question" class="reveal">
  <h2>Nobody Memes a Hard Question</h2>
  <p>The trolley problem has become, overwhelmingly, a joke. Multi-track drifting. The trolley that loops. Elaborate twelve-track variants where every option kills a different moral philosopher. The internet has produced thousands of these, and the sheer volume tells you something the philosophy department won't: people know the basic version is obvious. A genuinely hard question doesn't become a meme. It becomes a fight. The trolley problem became a punchline because the answer is clear enough that the only remaining move is to riff on it.</p>
  <p>Philippa Foot invented the scenario in 1967 as a weapon against utilitarianism. Judith Jarvis Thomson named it, spent decades analyzing it, then reversed herself in 2008 and argued that diverting the trolley is impermissible after all. Her colleagues mostly disagreed. The consensus held. The thought experiment built to destroy consequentialism ended up as its best advertisement: in a controlled, constrained, life-or-death decision with no additional information, the overwhelming majority of humans and philosophers reach the same conclusion. Save more people.</p>
  <p>Every semester, the reason this still gets taught as an open question is that the answer demands something people would rather not give. Pulling the lever means owning a death you caused. Not pulling it means owning four deaths you permitted while telling yourself you didn't choose. One of these is agonizing. The other is dishonest.</p>
  <p>Pull the lever. Save four lives. The guilt is the price of seriousness.</p>
</section>
